So I had an NVIDIA Shield Tablet that was recalled for a battery that was prone to overheating. Shipped it in for replacement, and received the brand new tablet with the new/safe battery. Never used it, so I opened it up, tested it, took pictures of it, and sold it on eBay. In the listing I selected "no returns accepted" (which of course means nothing on eBay for some reason), and described the item exactly as it arrived.

It sold, I shipped it out in a hard protective magnetic case, wrapped in plastic, and in a bubble mailer. Made sure to send it out a few hours after the sale was made. Did all my part as a seller, basically. Got the $300, and since I've been selling on eBay for so long, got the money instantly, withdrew it, and used it for textbooks.

Item arrived as described and with all items included. Buyer messages me asking "what my return policy is", so I tell her that I included in the listing I do not accept returns. I did however ask her for her reasoning, and she stated that the battery life did not last as long as she wanted, and that she has a second tablet to compare to and it lasted longer. I told her that this is the device itself and not an issue on my side. I suggested that she call NVIDIA about it if she had such a concern.

She continued demanding a refund and opened a return request, but in this one stated (presumably to meet buyer protection requirements and make it seem like the item was defective) that it "overheats and randomly shuts off". This obviously is not the case as I tested it extensively before selling it, and it is the post-recall tablet with the brand new safe battery specifically designed NOT to do this.

I offered a partial refund of $25 just to shut her up even though I have done nothing wrong, and she continues to decline. I am worried she might be trying to bait and switch me for her old tablet and return it as my own, but I don't know why she would do that.

Anyway, I've called eBay a few times and have to wait a few days to escalate the case.

So, if you want to see what's hiding under the .apk files, you could just do the steps below:

1) Rename your .apk file to .rar, it will simply go as a zipped file, after that.

2) Ass you can see in the exact .rar you just generated, the only related to class features, theme, is classes.dex. .dex formatting is used by android-sdk to compile all initial project classes to one(imagine it as a jar).

3) So, we need to get this jar, because we all know that there a free JAVA decompiler, called "JD-GUI". There is a programme called "dex2jar", which can be found here    

4) After downloading it, go to command line mode and guide through the directory that you have extracted the zipped file of dex2jar distribution.

5) Simply type in command line "dex2jar [directory of your .rar application file] " and hit <enter>.

6) You will then notice that a .jar file had just been generated. You can open this .jar will JD-GUI.

You are done!
